<cell id="cell-0"><language>kotlin</language>// Kotlin notebook
import jline.*
import jline.lang.*
import jline.lang.nodes.*
import jline.lang.processes.*
import jline.lang.constant.*
import jline.solvers.mva.*
import jline.util.matrix.*</cell id="cell-0">
<cell id="cell-1"><language>kotlin</language>// Define the workflow
val wf = Workflow("SerialWorkflow")</cell id="cell-1">
<cell id="cell-2"><language>kotlin</language>// Add activities with exponential service times
val A = wf.addActivity("A", Exp.fitMean(1.0))
val B = wf.addActivity("B", Exp.fitMean(2.0))
val C = wf.addActivity("C", Exp.fitMean(1.5))</cell id="cell-2">
<cell id="cell-3"><language>kotlin</language>// Define serial precedence
wf.addPrecedence(Workflow.serial(A, B, C))</cell id="cell-3">
<cell id="cell-4"><language>kotlin</language>// Convert to phase-type distribution
val ph = wf.toPH()</cell id="cell-4">
<cell id="cell-5"><language>kotlin</language>// Display results
println("Serial Workflow: A -> B -> C")
println("Activity means: A=1.0, B=2.0, C=1.5")
println("Expected total mean: ${1.0 + 2.0 + 1.5}")
println("Computed PH mean: ${ph.mean}")
println("Computed PH SCV: ${ph.sCV}")
println("Number of phases: ${ph.subgenerator.getNumRows()}")</cell id="cell-5">
<cell id="cell-6"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Serial Workflow Example

A simple workflow with three sequential activities.

**Workflow:** A -> B -> C

This example demonstrates:
- Creating a Workflow model
- Adding activities with exponential service time distributions
- Defining serial precedence relationships
- Converting the workflow to a phase-type distribution
- Computing workflow completion time statistics

The phase-type representation allows for efficient analysis of the total workflow execution time, including mean and squared coefficient of variation (SCV).</cell id="cell-6"></cell>